{{Infobox musical artist | name = Burkina Electric | image = | image_size = | landscape = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank --> | alt = | caption = | background = group_or_band | alias = | origin = [[Ouagadougou]], [[Burkina Faso]] | genre = [[Electronic music]] | years_active = {{start date|2007}}-present | label = [[Cantaloupe Music]] | associated_acts = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | current_members = [[Lukas Ligeti]], [[Mai Lingani]], [[Wende Blass]], [[Kurt Dahlke]], Wendy, Zoko Zoko | past_members = }} '''Burkina Electric''' is an electronic music group from [[Ouagadougou]], the capital city of [[Burkina Faso]]. They are one of Africa's first electronic acts.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=122979960 | title=Burkina Electric: 21st-Century African Music | work=NPR | date=26 January 2010 | accessdate=12 December 2014 | author=Kertzer, Jon}}</ref> Despite the group's African origins, they are mostly based in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.npr.org/2010/12/27/131242872/5-new-african-bands-that-blew-up-in-2010 | title=5 New African Bands That Ruled In 2010 | work=NPR | date=27 December 2010 | accessdate=14 December 2014 | author=Kertzer, Jon}}</ref> They were formed in 2007 when [[Mai Lingani]] (vocals), [[Wende K. Blass]] (guitar), [[Kurt Dahlke]] (electronics), and [[Lukas Ligeti]] (drummer) created the band for a tour of Austria. Lingani and Blass are from Burkina Faso, Dahlke (also known as Pyrolator) is from [[Düsseldorf]], Germany, and Ligeti is from Austria.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.laweekly.com/2011-09-22/music/music-picks-ravi-shankar-marilyn-scott-duran-duran-burkina-electric/ | title=Music Picks: Ravi Shankar, Marilyn Scott, Duran Duran, Burkina Electric | work=LA Weekly | date=22 September 2011 | accessdate=12 December 2014 | author=Fader, Lainna}}</ref> They released an EP called "Reem Tekre" in 2007 on the Atatak label.<ref name=allmusic/> The group contributed live music to the ballet "Itutu", which debuted in 2009 and was performed by [[Karole Armitage]]'s company Armitage Gone! Dance.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://nymag.com/arts/classicaldance/dance/features/60280/ | title=Ballet Electric | work=New York Magazine | date=25 October 2009 | accessdate=12 December 2014 | author=Milzoff, Rebecca}}</ref> Their first full-length album, ''Paspanga'', was released in early 2010.<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/burkina-electric-mn0002133220/biography | title=Burkina Electric Biography | work=AllMusic | accessdate=12 December 2014 | author=Jurek, Thom}}</ref> It was described as "fierce" by Richard Gehr in ''Spin'',<ref>{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=en6jizvGCTgC&pg=PA85 | title=Burkina Electric: Paspanga | work=Spin | date=April 2010 | accessdate=12 December 2014 | author=Gehr, Richard | pages=85}}</ref> and as "a sleek, kinetic album" by Nate Chinen.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/11/arts/music/11choi.html | title=New CDs | work=New York Times | date=10 January 2010 | accessdate=12 December 2014 | author=Chinen, Nate}}</ref> ==Discography== *''Reem Tekre'' EP (2007, Atatak) *''Paspanga'' (2010, Cantaloupe)
