{{Orphan|date=February 2009}}
The '''Path of the Mani''' is an ancient high-road from [[Kathmandu]], [[Nepal]], to the [[mountain pass]] of [[Langtang]] between the valleys of Nepal and the dry highlands of the [[Tibetan plateau]]. The pass is characterised by [[cairn]]s and aligned stones and slabs at the sides often with a form of [[mandala]] or inscription on them. The path played an important role in trade between [[India]], [[Nepal]] and [[Tibet]] where beasts of burden such as [[mule]]s, [[yak]]s and [[donkey]]s would carry furs, hides, yak tails, [[borax]], [[salt]], [[musk]] and medicinal herbs for trading.<ref>{{cite book|author=Willis, Michael|year=1999|title=Tibet:Life, Myth and Art|publisher=Duncan Baird Publishers Ltd}}</ref>

At Langtan a [[mantra]] guards the entrance to Tibet with a holy invocation of [[Avalokiteshvara]].

