{{Infobox building |name = Sporting d'Hiver |image = |location = Monaco |coordinates = |status = Demolished |start_date = |completion_date = 1932 |demolition_date = 2015 |building_type = |architectural_style = [[Beaux-Arts architecture]] |roof = |floor_count = |elevator_count = |cost = |floor_area = |architect = |structural_engineer= |main_contractor = |developer = |owner = [[Société des bains de mer de Monaco]] |management = |references = }} The '''Sporting d'Hiver''' was a historic building in [[Monaco]]. It was built in 1932 and demolished in 2015. Designed in the [[Beaux Arts architecture|Beaux Arts architectural style]], it was "once used to host glamorous parties and exhibitions for the world's [[High society (social class)|high society]]".<ref name="oppositionmounts"/>
==History== The building was completed in 1932.<ref name="lepointlameta">{{cite news|last1=Monier-Vinard|first1=Bruno|title=Monaco : la métamorphose du Carré d'or|url=http://www.lepoint.fr/immobilier/monaco-la-metamorphose-du-carre-d-or-26-05-2015-1931213_31.php|accessdate=February 5, 2016|work=Le Point|date=May 26, 2015}}</ref> It was designed in the [[Beaux Arts architecture|Beaux Arts architectural style]].<ref name="lepointlameta"/> The building was "once used to host glamorous parties and exhibitions for the world's [[High society (social class)|high society]]".<ref name="oppositionmounts">{{cite news|last1=Carpenter|first1=Elsa|title=Opposition mounts against Sporting d’Hiver demolition|url=http://www.rivieratimes.com/index.php/monaco-article/items/opposition-mounts-against-sporting-dhiver-demolition.html|accessdate=February 5, 2016|work=The Monaco Times|date=July 19, 2013}}</ref> By 1974, most society events had moved to the newly built [[Monte-Carlo Sporting]] in the [[Larvotto]] district.<ref name="petitfute2013">{{cite book|last1=Auzias|first1=Dominique|last2=Labourdette|first2=Jean-Paul|title=Monaco|date=2013|publisher=Le Petit Futé|location=Paris|page=68|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=_xmullH6DKkC&pg=PA68&dq=%22Sporting+d%27Hiver%22+monaco&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjxptjvlOHKAhUIzRQKHcVzBw4Q6AEIOTAF#v=onepage&q=%22Sporting%20d'Hiver%22%20monaco&f=false|accessdate=February 5, 2016}}</ref> In recent years, the Sporting d'Hiver was home to a cinema, SBM offices, and stores.<ref name="petitfute2013"/>
In 2008, [[Albert II, Prince of Monaco]] authorized the [[Société des bains de mer de Monaco]] (SBM) to demolish it and erect postmodern buildings instead.<ref name="oppositionmounts"/> Many Monegasque subjects and residents objected to the demolition, including [[Laurent Nouvion]], who serves as the president of the [[National Council (Monaco)|National Council]].<ref name="oppositionmounts"/> The building came down in June 2015.<ref name="monacomatintristefin">{{cite news|title=PHOTOS. Triste fin pour le Sporting d'Hiver à Monaco|url=http://archives.monacomatin.mc/monaco/photos-triste-fin-pour-le-sporting-dhiver-a-monaco.2260608.html|accessdate=February 5, 2016|work=Monaco-Matin|date=June 22, 2015}}</ref>
A new building, designed in the [[postmodern architecture|postmodern architectural style]] by [[Richard Rogers]], is in the works.<ref name="lepointlameta"/>
